[2] Latvia, Lithuania, Poland
Date: 28 Nov 2012
Source: DEFRA, International disease monitoring/Preliminary outbreak assessments, Reference: VITT/1200 BTV in Eastern Europe 2012 [summarised, edited]
http://www.defra.gov.uk/animal-diseases/files/poa-btv-20121128.pdf


Bluetongue Virus in Estonia, Latvia, Lithuania and Poland
-----------------------------------------
1. Disease Report
Lithuania reported in November 2012 that a calf exported to Spain in August 2012 had tested positive by PCR for BTV. As a result of this information, Lithuanian authorities tested a further number of cattle at the place of origin of the calf and found 15/51 more were also positive by ELISA. The serotype is unknown. (European Commission Fax Bluetongue 01/2012 - 13 Nov 2012).

On 19 Nov 2012, Latvia reported seropositive cattle (PCR negative) again, not serotyped (European Commission Fax Bluetongue 02/2012). According to the Ministry, samples were 1st detected as seropositive in September 2012 as a result of bulk milk testing.

On 22 Nov 2012 (European Commission Fax Bluetongue 03/2012), Poland reported 3 holdings in Podlaskie region, bordering Lithuania and Belarus, with PCR positive cattle. Serotyping was negative for BTV 1, 6, 8 and 11, but partial sequences aligned significantly with BTV-14.

Also on 22 Nov 2012, (European Commission Fax Bluetongue 04/2012) Estonia reported seropositive cattle on a farm in Saare region (an island in the Baltic Sea, west of the mainland). [But see item 3].

All countries have sent samples to the EU Reference Laboratory for BTV at the Pirbright Institute for serotyping. Preliminary results have confirmed the Polish samples as BTV-14 by real time RT-PCR and sera from Latvia to contain BTV-14 antibodies. Serum samples from Lithuania are still being investigated [but see item 1], and to date, samples from Estonia have not been received. Clinical disease has not been reported associated with this possible infection.

2. Situation Assessment
The most likely pathways for disease introduction would be in live animals, infected vectors, or possibly as a result of vaccination with a live vaccine. [The latter has been confirmed in the meantime; see item 1 above].

On a regional basis, the country which has most recently reported BTV-14 is Russia in Smolensk region, West Russia, where cattle, sheep and goats were reported as infected (OIE, 2011). It is not known whether further surveillance was carried out around the infected premises or in any other susceptible animals since this report [see item 3].

The recent reports of Schmallenberg virus from Poland and Estonia would suggest that vectors are active and likely to have been capable of transmitting aroboviruses over the summer months.

A vaccine is manufactured by the Onderstepoort Company, which is a combination live attenuated vaccine against BTV 1, 4, 6, 12 and 14. It is not suitable for use in the EU because of the risk of reversion to virulence following passage, possible transmission of the strain via vectors, potential to recombine, and possible teratrogenic effects. In addition, the vaccines have only been validated for use in sheep. Vaccine strains have appeared before in Europe due to illegal use, notably BTV-6 and BTV-11, causing limited spread and no clinical disease. This route of introduction cannot be ruled out yet.

BTV-14 has been reported in the USA previously, particularly in the Southeast States (MacLachlan, 2006). In the USA, some disease may occur as a result of infection with various bluetongue serotypes, particularly in sheep, but not in other species. Therefore, these bluetongue serotypes are not considered a high priority in terms of impact, and vaccination is rarely used in sheep and not at all in cattle; BTV-14 is understood to be one such serotype.

3. Conclusions
According to TRACES [Trade Control and Expert System], the EU electronic trade notification system [for monitoring the movements of animals and products of animal origin both within and coming from outside of the EU], there have been no imports into the UK of live cattle or small ruminants in the last 6 months from Estonia, Latvia or Lithuania. However, there have been a handful of cattle from Poland. These will be traced. Future consignments will also be checked for compliance with health certification.

Several of these East European countries are likely to be entering the vector-free period, and, therefore, the risk of spread is reduced; nevertheless, a new serotype entering the EU, even with few clinical signs, is always a concern.

4. Authors
Dr Helen Roberts
Dr Carrie Batten

5. References
1. All Commission Legislation is available from the Commission website http://eur-lex.europa.eu/RECH_mot.do.
2. FAOSTAT (2012)
3. MacLachlan, N.J. (2006) Bluetongue vaccines in the United States. http://ec.europa.eu/food/animal/diseases/controlmeasures/bluetongue_vaccines_usa.pdf.
4. OIE (2011) Bluetongue in Russia: Immediate Notification Report 30/12/2011 Report No. 11439 http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/temp/reports/en_imm_0000011439_20111230_121101.pdf.

