[3] Estonia, results pending
Date: Mon 3 Dec 2012
Source: Baltic-course [summarised, edited]
http://www.baltic-course.com/eng/markets_and_companies/?doc=66851


Analysis results from a lab in the UK that arrived at the end of last week indicate that a beef cattle animal in the Saaremaa island that was suspected to be suffering from bluetongue disease does not have the disease, but to be completely certain, vets will conduct blood tests on 900 cattle and sheep in the Saaremaa island, LETA/Saarte Haal ["Islands Voice"] writes.

Estonian Veterinary and Food Board director general Ago Partel told Saarte Haal that the analyses conducted last week in the Pirbright laboratory in the UK indicate that while the test made on 19 Nov 2012 showed that the animal had the virus, the test from 25 Nov 2012 is completely clean.

Partel said that it is now 99.9 percent certain that there wasn't any virus, but a final confirmation will arrive in 2 weeks. According to the law, since an earlier test showed the presence of the virus, around 900 blood samples must be collected from cattle and sheep in 20-km radius and sent to the Veterinary and Food Laboratory in Tartu to be tested.

[Byline: Juhan Tere]

