[4] Russia, update
Date: Tue 4 Dec 2012 [accessed]
Source: All-Russian Research Institute for Animal Health (FGBI-ARRIAH), Vladimir. Office of Veterinary Surveillance, report on the epizootic situation in the Russian Federation for the 1st half of 2012. Bluetongue (pages 33-34) [trans. Faina Golender, summarised, edited]
http://www.fsvps.ru/fsvps-docs/ru/iac/2012/files/reports/iac_report_1_2012.pdf


The disease [bluetongue] has not been recorded in the Russian Federation since 1994. 1st cases were diagnosed in imported cattle in 2008.

On 26 Dec 2011, Russia notified the OIE about the identification of bluetongue virus serotype 14 in the Smolensk region (Urgansk district) in 5 head of cattle, one goat and 4 sheep.

In the 1st quarter of 2012, bluetongue disease was detected and registered in the Smolensk region (5 cattle) and in the region of Niznii Novgorod (4 cattle). Seropositive animals continued to be identified in the Smolensk region (230 cattle) and in Kaluga region (126 cattle). No seropositive animals have been detected during the 2nd quarter of 2012.

In accordance with the data obtained from the Center for Veterinary Medicine, 15 074 head of cattle were serologically examined during the 1st half of 2012, of which 362 were positive (Kaluga, Smolensk, Niznii Novgorod, Tyumen regions).

Map: The territories of the Russian Federation where BT seropositive cattle have been detected during 2012 [See map on page 34 at the source URL].
Legend: Red areas - Surveillance undertaken, BT-positive. Green areas - Surveillance undertaken, BT negative. Gray areas - no surveillance.

