[The contents of the moderator comment below have been modified from the original report that was sent by email. - Mod. MPP]

[The following information on the live-attenuated BTV South African vaccine is available on the web-site of the producer, Onderstepoort Biological Products (OBP):
"The vaccine is presented as a series of 3 separate injections with different serotypes of bluetongue virus in each bottle. The bottles are marked A, B and C and must be injected in the following sequence: A, 1st, B, 3 weeks later, and the bottle marked C, 3 weeks after B. If necessary, this interval can be longer but never shorter than 3 weeks. It is necessary to inject the full series, A, B and C in order to get the widest possible protection."

The user's instructions above are intended for the South African and Namibian markets. See "Bluetongue vaccine for sheep" at http://www.obpvaccines.co.za/Cms_Data/Contents/OBPDB/Folders/Product/~contents/GL42GL73FYR4L9CU/2013%20Bluetongue_PI.pdf.

Details on the contents of the different 3 bottles are available in the paper "The use of vaccination in the control of bluetongue in southern Africa" by B. Dungu, T. Gerdes and T. Smit (2004), Veterinaria Italiana, 40 (4), 616-622.

According to the said paper, bottle A includes BTV serotypes 1, 4, 6, 12, 14. Bottle B includes serotypes 3, 8, 9, 10, 11. Bottle C includes the serotypes 2, 5, 7, 13, 19.

Vaccine strain BTV-6 (Germany, Netherlands, 2008) is included in bottle A, similarly to BTV-14. It may have been used to protect against BTV-4 and/or BTV-1, which have been circulating in several European countries (see FEFRA's map, item 1).

Vaccine strain BTV-11 (Belgium, 2008) is included in bottle B, which may have been used to protect against BTV-8.

Where, when, and to which animal species have these vaccines been applied remains to be investigated.

So far, the 3 vaccine strains have not been shown to be involved in clinical disease. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1z-D.]
